04246nam a22006615i 9780812298062DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122980627 a10.9783/97808122980622doi  a(DE-B1597)590437  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0510002bisacsh1 aBhadra-Heintz, John I. B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Tyranny Against Itself :bIntimate Partner Violence on the Margins of Bogotá /cJohn I. B. Bhadra-Heintz. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b6 bw  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. La Zona Quinta -- tChapter 2. Possible -- tChapter 3. Permissible -- tChapter 4. Stakes -- tChapter 5. Contradictions and Consciousness -- tChapter 6. Response -- tAppendix 1. Toward a Tengentic Approach -- tAppendix 2. Therapeutic Windows and Transformative Care -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUsme, one of the peripheral districts surrounding Bogotá, Colombia, is one of the poorest, most populous, and most marginalized outer districts of the city, with a high concentration of indigenous occupants. Over eighty percent of Usme’s women have experienced partner violence or some kind of partner-controlling behavior.How does one go about understanding the perpetration of partner violence? Based on ethnographic work with survivors, responders, and most of all the perpetrators of this kind of abuse, scholar John I.B. Bhadra-Heintz explores this issue in A Tyranny Against Itself. Throughout this study, Bhadra-Heintz examines how this violence is made possible, how it is positioned to be permissible socially, and what is at stake for those who are involved.This violence is examined as a question of sovereignty on the intimate scale. Not the product of a particular cultural pathology, a phenomenon that can otherwise be otherized, this book seeks instead to find the lines of connection, and contradiction, that tie these intimate acts of violence into broader regimes of power. In a community so profoundly shaped by centuries of political conflict, only through this kind of approach can new apertures for engagement be found. Through them, this book outlines new vulnerabilities in this form of abuse, and along the way imagines new ways of escaping from these everyday acts of intimate terror and the broader systems of violence in which they are involved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aCaribbean Studies.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLatin American Studies.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229806240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812298062423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812298062/original  a978-3-11-076767-4  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK